\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape up
Management should actively support security within the organization through
 clear direction, demonstrated commitment, explicit assigment, and acknowledgmen
t of information security responsibilities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape up
Information security activities should be co-ordinated by representatives
 from different parts of the organization with relevant roles and job functions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape up
All information security responsibilities should be clearly defined.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape up
A management authorization process for new information processing facilities
 should be defined and implemented.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape up
Requirements for confidentiality or non-disclosure agreements reflecting
 the organization's needs for the protection of information should be identified
 and regularly reviewed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape up
Appropriate contacts with relevant authorities should be maintained.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape up
Appropriate contacts with special interest groups or other specialist security
 forums and professional associations should be maintained.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape up
The organization's approach to managing information security and its implementio
n (i.e.
 control objectives, controls, policies, processes, and procedures) should
 be reviewd independently at planned intervals, or when significant changes
 to the security implementation occur.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\shape up
